Nick Scholfield will ride Jim Culloty's horse, Spring Heeled, in the Grand National at Aintree on April 11, after initially being expected to ride Sam Winner, who may not run. Trainer Paul Nicholls decided it was unfair to keep Scholfield tied to a potentially non-running horse when a definite contender was available. Scholfield, who has experience in the Grand National, will visit Culloty's stable in Ireland to prepare. Spring Heeled, a previous winner at the Cheltenham Festival, has had limited runs since last July. Culloty will also have Lord Windermere in the race, ridden by Robbie McNamara. Meanwhile, Luke Morris made history by becoming the first jockey to achieve 100 winners in an All Weather Flat racing season.
Dr. Mehmet Oz is facing criticism from some faculty members at Columbia University for promoting "unsubstantiated medicine" on his talk show, which they argue damages the university's reputation. However, eight faculty members defended him in an op-ed, acknowledging his strong record as a physician at Columbia while criticizing his TV methods. They highlighted concerns about the lack of evidence behind many of his recommendations and suggested that he should include disclaimers on his show regarding the validity of his advice. Despite the backlash, Dr. Oz expressed pride in the feedback from his colleagues and maintained that his show serves a broader purpose beyond medical advice. He also dismissed the criticisms as part of a conspiracy linked to his views on genetically modified foods, asserting that he has never judged GMO products. Columbia University emphasized its commitment to academic freedom in response to the controversy.
The Duchess of Cornwall has launched her own honey, produced from her Wiltshire garden, with 250 jars available at £20 each, benefiting the Medical Detection Dogs charity. This initiative comes amid a growing demand for gourmet honey, with high-end sales at Selfridges increasing by 45% since last year. A taste test of various gourmet honeys reveals the Duchess's honey, described as delicately perfumed with chamomile hints, received a perfect score for its delicious flavor and attractive packaging. Other notable honeys include Duchy Originals Scottish Heather Honey, praised for its unique taste, and Wedderspoon Gold Organic Rata Honey, which has a rare flavor reminiscent of pine. Tregothnan Cornish Floral Manuka is recognized for its rarity and high price, while Vasilissa Greek Honey, infused with edible gold, is highlighted for its luxurious appeal. Other honeys, such as Alemany Rosemary Honey and Welsh Chunk Honeycomb, received mixed reviews, with some disappointing in taste despite their premium pricing. Overall, the article showcases the diverse and luxurious world of gourmet honey, emphasizing both taste and presentation.
Aubrey de Grey, a 51-year-old biomedical theorist, believes that aging is a disease that can be cured, potentially allowing humans to live for centuries or even millennia. Despite his unconventional lifestyle and appearance, he has garnered support from influential figures in Silicon Valley, including Peter Thiel and Google co-founders, who are interested in anti-aging research. De Grey argues that advancements in technology will enable the repair and replacement of damaged cells, leading to extended lifespans. While many academics criticize his theories as unrealistic, he remains optimistic, claiming that the first person to live to 1,000 has already been born. He acknowledges the challenges of overpopulation and resource management but believes society will adapt. De Grey's eccentric personality and lifestyle choices, including his unconventional marriage and relationships, add to his controversial public image.
Scientists have made a significant advancement in clean hydrogen power by developing a new molecular catalyst that efficiently generates hydrogen from water, reducing reliance on fossil fuels. Researchers from the University of Bath and Yale University created this catalyst to improve the water electrolysis process, which traditionally wastes energy during hydrogen production. The new catalyst enhances the oxidation reaction, minimizing energy loss and making hydrogen production more economical. This breakthrough could facilitate the storage of renewable energy, such as solar and wind, in the form of hydrogen, which can be used on demand. The team is in discussions with energy companies to implement this technology on a larger scale, aiming to contribute to a sustainable hydrogen economy. The research highlights the importance of generating clean hydrogen to support environmentally friendly applications.
A recent study suggests that Fisher-Price magnets from the 1970s and 1980s may have influenced the color-letter associations of individuals with synesthesia, a neurological condition where senses are involuntarily linked. Researchers from Stanford University analyzed data from 6,588 participants and found that about 6% of synesthetes learned their color-letter pairings from these toys, with the figure rising to 15% among those born shortly after the magnets were introduced. The study indicates that exposure to these colorful toys may condition synesthetic associations, although it does not claim that the toys cause synesthesia. Other cultural influences and toys may also play a role in shaping these associations.
Hannah Overton, a Texas mother who spent seven years in prison for the murder of her adopted son, Andrew Burd, will not face new charges after her conviction was overturned due to ineffective counsel. Overton, 37, was released shortly before Christmas and celebrated with her family upon learning that prosecutors had dropped all charges against her. The Nueces County district attorney, Mark Skurka, initially indicated he would pursue capital murder charges again, but later decided against it after reviewing the case and consulting with key witnesses and medical experts. Overton's conviction was overturned last year, with an appellate court noting issues with her original trial, including the prosecution's alleged withholding of evidence. The case revolved around Andrew's death from salt poisoning, which Overton's defense argued was accidental and linked to his eating disorder, pica. Overton's family has consistently supported her, and she expressed gratitude for the outcome, emphasizing her faith throughout the ordeal.
Mary Cartwright, a 91-year-old great-grandmother, revisited the Drakelow Shadow Factory in Kidderminster, Worcestershire, where she worked as a wartime scientist testing metal for aircraft engines 70 years ago. At 20, she was the only woman in her department at the underground factory, which employed over 700 people during World War II. The factory, built to protect production from bombings, was part of a network of 26 underground sites established for military aircraft and tank production. Cartwright recalled her experiences, including analyzing metal samples and taking photographs for documentation. After the war, she became a teacher and later reflected on her time at Drakelow as a bustling environment, contrasting it with its current quiet state. The site, which has undergone various transformations since the war, is now privately owned, with efforts underway to establish it as a museum.
This weekend, top-ranked UFC featherweights Chad Mendes and Ricardo Lamas will face off in a potentially title-eliminating bout in Fairfax. Both fighters have previously lost to current champion Jose Aldo, with Mendes expressing confidence in Aldo's abilities against Conor McGregor, who has been the focus of recent discussions. Mendes and Lamas have shown mutual respect leading up to their fight, with Mendes believing he is slightly better in all aspects. Lamas acknowledges the challenge Mendes presents but is determined to perform well to secure a title shot. The event also features a co-main fight between exciting lightweight fighters Jorge Masvidal and Al Iaquinta. The fight will be broadcast live on BT Sport 1.
An explosion at a chemical plant in Zhangzhou, Fujian province, injured six people and caused a large fire. The plant produces paraxylene, a chemical linked to cancer, and the blast occurred at an oil storage facility following an oil leak. Five of the injured were treated for cuts from broken glass. Over 600 firefighters responded, and the fire is now under control. Residents reported hearing the explosion and feeling tremors. The plant has a history of controversy, having previously faced protests over pollution concerns, leading to its relocation from a densely populated area.
Scott Sibella, president of the MGM Grand, assures attendees of the upcoming Fight of the Century between Floyd Mayweather and Manny Pacquiao that there will be no shortage of beer, referencing a previous event where fans depleted supplies. With an expected crowd of 100,000, the MGM is preparing extensively, including stocking half a million beer bottles and planning for 50,000 visitors daily. The hotel, which features 7,000 rooms and a 16,000-capacity arena, is also focused on safety, implementing new crowd control measures after past incidents. The economic impact of the fight is projected to exceed $1 billion, highlighting Las Vegas's shift from a gambling-centric to a broader entertainment destination. The event will also feature closed-circuit viewing options and a first-ever admission fee for the weigh-in, with proceeds going to charity. Sibella emphasizes the importance of a well-executed plan for both the fight and the overall experience for guests.
Samantha Cameron made her first solo appearance of the general election in Rochester and Strood, a stronghold for Ukip, to support Tory candidate Kelly Tolhurst. This visit comes as the Conservatives aim to reclaim the seat from Mark Reckless, who defected from the Tories to Ukip. During her visit to Abbey Court School, Mrs. Cameron engaged with students and expressed her support for her husband, Prime Minister David Cameron, ahead of a major debate. The Conservatives are focused on this key seat, especially after Reckless won the by-election with a significant majority. Mrs. Cameron is expected to make more political appearances as the campaign progresses, while David Cameron acknowledged that their personal time may be limited due to campaign commitments.
The shooting of unarmed black man Walter Scott by police officer Michael Slager in North Charleston, South Carolina, has sparked national outrage, with local residents expressing a lack of surprise due to a history of unaddressed complaints against the police. Community members believe the police department focuses on minor offenses and fails to hold officers accountable. Slager's personnel file shows minimal evidence of misconduct, despite a previous excessive force complaint that was dismissed without thorough investigation. Video evidence contradicts Slager's claims of feeling threatened, showing him shooting Scott in the back as he fled. The incident highlights broader issues in policing, including a culture that often dismisses citizen complaints and a legal system that favors police in misconduct cases. Local leaders are calling for an independent review board to address police complaints, as many believe that better oversight could have prevented Scott's death.
The Liberal Democrats are bracing for a significant loss of at least 20 MPs, potentially reducing their total from 57 to the 'thirties' due to a sharp decline in support, currently around 8% in opinion polls. Party leader Nick Clegg is focusing on a targeted campaign in 60 key constituencies, emphasizing the need to win marginal seats to maintain influence in a possible coalition government after the May 7 election. Despite the bleak outlook, Clegg remains optimistic about the party's campaigning abilities, likening their efforts to running multiple by-elections across the country. Polls indicate a competitive race among the Conservatives, Labour, and Ukip, with varying leads, suggesting an uncertain election outcome.
Former QPR manager Harry Redknapp, 68, believes he still has much to contribute to football but is selective about potential opportunities, having recently declined a lucrative coaching offer abroad. He resigned from QPR in February due to knee issues, although he later suggested that external agendas influenced his departure. Redknapp is set to return to coaching for a charity match on May 31, where he will lead a team against Leyton Orient Legends. He expressed a desire to return to management only if the right opportunity arises, emphasizing that it’s not about the money but rather the right fit. He praised current Bournemouth manager Eddie Howe for his success, as the club leads the Championship and aims for promotion. Additionally, Redknapp is advocating for prostate cancer awareness, a cause close to him after losing a friend to the disease. Tickets for the charity match are available online.
Moose Toys' headquarters in Cheltenham, Melbourne, is likened to a Google-like environment, featuring creative spaces such as a beanstalk meeting room, toy testing areas, and recreational facilities like a gym and table tennis. Employees are encouraged to collaborate and brainstorm away from their desks, fostering a fun and innovative atmosphere. The company emphasizes employee well-being through social events, team-building activities, and recognition programs, including a unique Employee of the Year award. Moose Toys, a family-owned business for over 25 years, employs around 100 staff in Melbourne and has a global presence. The company has received accolades for its products, including the 2015 Girl Toy of the Year Award for Shopkins Small Mart.
A high-speed passenger train derailed near Split, Croatia, on Friday, resulting in at least six fatalities and 45 injuries. The train was traveling from Zagreb to Split when it went off the tracks about 20 kilometers from its destination. Croatian police have initiated an investigation into the incident, which has been described as a significant tragedy.
A senior writer for the Australian Financial Review, Geoff Winestock, has defended SBS journalist Scott McIntyre, who was fired for his controversial tweets about Anzac Day, labeling Anzacs as "racist yobs" and calling the day a "death cult." McIntyre's tweets, which described Anzac Day as the "cultification of an imperialist invasion" and accused Australian soldiers of war crimes, sparked public outrage and led to calls for his dismissal, including the trending hashtag #sackScottMcIntyre. SBS Managing Director Michael Ebeid condemned McIntyre's comments as "highly inappropriate and disrespectful," stating they did not reflect the views of the network. While some defended McIntyre's right to free speech, many criticized his remarks as offensive, especially given the centenary of the Gallipoli landings. SBS has since issued an apology for any offense caused by McIntyre's comments.
In the first week of the election campaign, Labour leader Ed Miliband received over £1.6 million in donations from trade unions, significantly outpacing the Conservative Party's £500,000. The Labour Party's funding heavily relies on unions, with 84% of their £1.9 million coming from just three unions, including a £1 million contribution from Unite. Critics argue that Labour's policies, such as raising corporation tax and nationalizing railways, reflect its dependence on union support. Meanwhile, the Conservatives received donations from various sources, including hedge fund donors, and faced criticism for unrealistic spending pledges. The TaxPayers' Alliance emphasized the need for honesty regarding deficit reduction challenges.
Joshua Sweet, a 20-year-old from Birmingham, was sentenced to a three-year community order after pleading guilty to burglary and sexual assault, having served only two months in remand. The victim, a 24-year-old teacher, was left traumatized and psychologically scarred by the incident, which occurred when Sweet broke into her home and assaulted her while she was asleep. Despite the serious nature of the crime, the judge, Mary Stacey, acknowledged the victim's trauma but opted for a community sentence due to Sweet's early plea and time served. This decision has drawn criticism from victim support advocates, who argue that such offenders should face harsher penalties. Sweet is required to complete 150 hours of unpaid work and register as a sex offender for five years, and a restraining order was placed to prevent him from contacting the victim.
The shooting of Walter Scott, a 50-year-old African-American father-of-four, by Officer Michael Slager in Charleston, South Carolina, has sparked widespread outrage and grief on social media, particularly among celebrities. Scott was shot while fleeing from the officer, who initially claimed he feared for his life. However, video evidence showed Slager shooting Scott in the back multiple times. Celebrities like Michelle Williams, Janelle Monáe, and Questlove expressed their sorrow and anger over the incident, with Questlove criticizing the justification of the shooting. Slager has been charged with murder, and South Carolina Senator Tim Scott described the death as "unnecessary and avoidable." The incident has reignited discussions about police violence and accountability.
In Baghdad, Iraq, six gay men were killed by members of their tribe in two separate incidents over the past 10 days, according to an Interior Ministry official. The most recent attack occurred in Sadr City, where two men were shot after being disowned by their families. This followed a tribal meeting that targeted the victims. Earlier, on March 26, four other men were also fatally shot in the same area under similar circumstances. Additionally, a cafe popular among the LGBTQ+ community in Sadr City was set on fire.
Vestiaire Collective has listed a made-to-measure pink crocodile Hermes Birkin bag embellished with rubies for £140,000, potentially making it Britain's most expensive handbag. The bag is exclusive and cannot be purchased in stores, with experts suggesting it is a good investment due to its rarity and the brand's controlled supply. Hermes Birkin bags are known for their quality and craftsmanship, making them highly desirable among wealthy women. The article highlights the brand's history and the iconic status of the Birkin and Kelly bags, mentioning celebrity owners like Victoria Beckham and Kim Kardashian. The Hermes brand is renowned for its luxury leather goods, with each handbag crafted by a single artisan.
World heavyweight boxing champion Wladimir Klitschko is focused on his upcoming title defense against Bryant Jennings while expressing deep concern for the ongoing conflict in Ukraine, his homeland. He described the situation as shocking and upsetting, emphasizing that Ukraine is not the aggressor in the war with Russia. Klitschko highlighted the tragic division between Ukrainians and Russians and the daily loss of life in Ukraine. He remains hopeful for a democratic future for Ukraine with the support of the international community, rejecting any attempts to revert to a Soviet-style dictatorship. Klitschko stays informed about the situation in Ukraine through his brother Vitali, a political figure, and he frequently visits home. As he prepares for his 18th title defense, Klitschko also reflects on his new role as a father and his desire for peace in the world.
Bruce Jenner will document his transition into a woman in an upcoming eight-episode docu-series on E!, starting July 27. However, his sons Burt, Brandon, and Brody Jenner, along with stepdaughter Kim Kardashian, are reportedly concerned about him revealing too much of his journey on reality TV. They have advised him to slow down and keep some aspects private, fearing that the series might undermine his accomplishments. Despite their concerns, Bruce believes the show will educate viewers and foster empathy. The series will be produced in consultation with GLAAD and aims to provide an unfiltered look at his transition. While his children expressed pride in him, they also reflected on their complex relationships with him due to his absence during their formative years. Bruce has stated that he is committed to sharing his story, emphasizing the importance of being true to himself.
Channel 4 news presenter Krishnan Guru-Murthy faced an awkward moment during an interview with Robert Downey Jr. when he asked about the actor's past with drugs. Downey Jr. abruptly walked out, expressing confusion over the direction of the conversation. This incident highlights a trend where celebrities, including Naomi Campbell, Robert Pattinson, Justin Bieber, Peter Andre, and Rihanna, have similarly exited interviews when questioned about their personal lives. Each case involved uncomfortable or probing questions that led to the interviewees cutting the discussions short, often leaving interviewers stunned.
A 16-year-old Syrian boy, Amjad Yaaqub, recounted witnessing Islamic State (ISIS) militants playing football with a severed head in the besieged Yarmouk refugee camp in Damascus. He was attacked by the militants searching for his brother, a member of a Palestinian rebel group. The camp has seen horrific violence since ISIS took control of 90% of it, leading to over 200 deaths in a week. Refugees described daily atrocities, including the murder of children in front of their parents. Many families have fled to nearby areas held by the Syrian army, with reports indicating that nearly 200 people had already died from malnutrition before the recent assault. Yarmouk, once home to 160,000 Palestinian refugees, has been devastated by years of conflict and siege. Residents shared their harrowing experiences, highlighting the drastic change in their lives since ISIS's arrival, which has brought fear and destruction.
Wigan Athletic's new manager, Gary Caldwell, expressed a desire for his team to fight hard against relegation from the Sky Bet Championship. However, Martyn Waghorn's reckless red card during a match against Millwall hindered their efforts. Millwall capitalized on Waghorn's dismissal, with Jimmy Abdou scoring the first goal and Magaye Gueye adding a second in stoppage time, securing a 2-0 victory. The match was marked by intense confrontations, resulting in three red cards—two for Wigan and one for Millwall. Millwall's win keeps their hopes alive in the relegation battle, while Wigan remains seven points from safety. Caldwell criticized Millwall's aggressive style, contrasting it with his team's approach to playing football. Millwall's manager, Neil Harris, celebrated the victory, highlighting Abdou's rare goal and the team's determination.
Many British workers continue to buy expensive lunchtime takeaways instead of preparing meals at home, spending an average of £1,840 annually. Research suggests that making lunch at home could save individuals up to £1,300 a year. Simple lunch ideas include cheese, crackers, and charcuterie, which can be easily assembled at the office. Food52's 'Not Sad Desk Lunch' series offers a variety of recipes, from simple options to more complex dishes like steamed buns and Vietnamese banh mi sandwiches. The article highlights the cost-effectiveness and health benefits of homemade lunches, providing several recipes and suggestions for easy-to-make meals.
Tourists can book a unique £3,500 trip to Russia's Durminskoye Reserve to experience a week-long safari near the endangered Siberian tiger. Offered by Natural World Safaris, the trip allows guests to explore the tigers' natural habitat, set camera traps, and learn from conservationist Alexander Batalov, who has dedicated 20 years to protecting these big cats. Accommodations are basic, and while sightings of the elusive tigers are not guaranteed, guests will engage in activities like tracking footprints and collecting conservation data. The Siberian tiger population is critically low, with fewer than 400 individuals remaining in the wild, making this an exceptional wildlife travel opportunity.
A 24-year-old Algerian jihadi, Sid Ahmed Ghlam, was arrested in Paris after being linked to the murder of Aurelie Chatelain, a 33-year-old fitness instructor. Ghlam, who shot himself in the leg before his arrest, was found with weapons and documents related to ISIS and Al Qaeda at his residence. He was reportedly planning attacks on churches in Paris, having communicated with a contact in Syria about targeting them. French authorities confirmed that DNA evidence connects him to Chatelain's murder, which occurred just hours before his arrest. Ghlam, a computer science student known to intelligence services, had been under surveillance and was considered a potential candidate for joining ISIS in Syria. His arrest follows heightened security concerns in France after previous terrorist attacks.
Researchers have conducted a comprehensive study of the microbiomes of the uncontacted Yanomami tribe in the Amazon, revealing that their bacteria diversity is the highest ever reported in humans. This study highlights the significant impact of modern diets and lifestyles on human microbiomes. The Yanomami, who live in remote areas of Brazil and Venezuela and maintain a hunter-gatherer lifestyle, have not been exposed to industrialized society, antibiotics, or Western diets. The findings suggest that studying such isolated populations could provide insights into beneficial bacteria lost in modern life. The research also uncovered that Yanomami bacteria possess natural antibiotic resistance genes, indicating that these traits exist independently of antibiotic exposure. The study emphasizes the importance of understanding microbiomes in non-Western populations before globalization affects their health. Additionally, the article discusses the historical context of blood samples taken from the Yanomami without consent in the 1960s, which were recently returned after a long struggle for their repatriation.
Protests in South Africa have erupted against statues of colonial figures, particularly targeting Cecil Rhodes, whose statue was recently removed from the University of Cape Town after being vandalized. Young black protesters defaced various memorials, including those of Queen Victoria, King George V, and other historical figures associated with colonialism and Afrikaner nationalism. The protests have sparked a debate about the legacy of these figures, with some calling for the removal of their statues while others demand protection for their heritage. The South African government has expressed support for addressing the country's colonial past, although it does not endorse violent actions. Tensions remain high, with some groups feeling their history is under threat, while many South Africans seek a balanced approach to reconciliation and social justice.
Lizzi Crawford, a 32-year-old mother from Stoke-on-Trent, lost over seven stone after a child on a bus mistakenly asked if she was pregnant, prompting her to change her unhealthy lifestyle. Weighing 20 stone and living on a diet of takeaways and alcohol, the embarrassing comment motivated her to adopt healthier eating habits and engage in fitness activities, including self-defense classes and Hourglass training. Despite facing a cervical cancer diagnosis in 2012, Lizzi successfully battled both the disease and her weight, now weighing 12.5 stone. She credits her gym community for support and has found joy in fitness, which has improved her physical and mental well-being, allowing her to be more active with her children. Her mother praised her transformation and commitment to maintaining a healthier lifestyle.
Prosecutor Nafir Afzal has expressed concern that many British teenagers view ISIS as "pop idols," similar to celebrities like One Direction and Justin Bieber, which increases the risk of radicalization. He warned that without significant changes in how Britain addresses terrorism, the country could face another major attack like the 7/7 bombings. Afzal emphasized the need for a community-led approach to counter radicalization, suggesting that young Muslim role models could be more effective than traditional authority figures. He criticized the portrayal of ISIS as having a religious or political basis, arguing that they are merely "narcissistic, murderous cowboys." His comments come amid reports of a Labour councillor's son attempting to join an extremist group in Syria. Afzal, who recently left the Crown Prosecution Service, has been a prominent advocate for justice in sensitive cases, including high-profile child abuse prosecutions.
Paul Downton has been dismissed as managing director of the England and Wales Cricket Board (ECB) following England's poor performance in the World Cup, where they failed to progress past the group stage. The decision, made by new ECB chief executive Tom Harrison and chairman-elect Colin Graves, was unanimous among board members, who criticized Downton's management style. Downton's tenure included controversial decisions such as the sacking of Kevin Pietersen and Alastair Cook as one-day captain. The ECB plans to create a new role of director of England cricket, which will focus on performance accountability, with former England captain Michael Vaughan and Andrew Strauss as potential candidates. Despite Downton's departure, Harrison stated that the position of current coach Peter Moores remains secure, and the restructuring aims to foster a high-performance environment for the future.
James Haskell, the captain of the London Wasps, celebrated the release of "Avengers: Age of Ultron" by posting a serious-looking photo on Instagram dressed as Iron Man, a character played by Robert Downey Jr. The movie premiered at Westfield London, attracting many fans. Haskell, who returned to Wasps in 2012 after playing in France, Japan, and New Zealand, has made over 100 appearances for the club and has earned 57 caps for the England rugby team.
Celebrities are participating in the #SelfieEsteem campaign by sharing unfiltered selfies on social media to promote self-acceptance and combat low self-esteem. Notable figures like Susanna Reid, Nancy Dell'Olio, and Piers Morgan have joined the initiative, which highlights the pressure many feel to present a perfect image online. A survey by Good Morning Britain revealed that women typically take six selfies before posting, while men take four, with many avoiding mirrors due to low self-esteem. The campaign aims to encourage individuals to embrace their natural appearance, as many women and men express dissatisfaction with their looks. The survey also indicated that a significant number of women worry about passing body confidence issues to their children. The response to the campaign has been positive, with many viewers sharing their own unfiltered selfies.
Imran Uddin, a 25-year-old student at the University of Birmingham, was sentenced to four months in jail for hacking into university computers to alter his exam marks using keyboard spying devices. He purchased the equipment online, which allowed him to record staff keystrokes and obtain their passwords to access their accounts. Uddin changed his grades, including raising one from 57% to 73%. His actions were discovered when staff found the devices during a computer upgrade. He admitted to six charges under the Computer Misuse Act. The judge emphasized the need for deterrence, stating that Uddin's actions could undermine public confidence in the degree system. Uddin's defense highlighted the pressure he felt as the first in his family to attend university.
Democratic presidential candidate Hillary Clinton was seen enjoying a leisurely afternoon stroll with her husband Bill in Chappaqua, New York, while her campaign vans received maintenance at a local body shop. The couple wore matching blue attire and were spotted walking hand-in-hand in a park. Clinton is set to resume her campaign in New Hampshire, where she will hold discussions at local businesses over two days. Recent reports highlighted her high earnings from paid appearances, which exceed those of top CEOs, although her overall income is lower when considering a full work week. Clinton's campaign has faced scrutiny over her perceived disconnect with everyday Americans, a challenge she faced in her previous presidential run. Meanwhile, her campaign vans were cleaned and inspected in preparation for upcoming events.
Leeds striker Steve Morison expressed surprise at the chaotic situation surrounding the club, particularly after six players withdrew from the squad due to injuries before a match against Charlton. This incident is part of a turbulent period for Leeds United, with manager Neil Redfearn describing the withdrawals as a "freakish set of events." Former captain Trevor Cherry criticized the players for their last-minute withdrawals, calling for their dismissal and questioning the legitimacy of their injuries. The ongoing turmoil has raised concerns about team spirit and management stability, especially with Redfearn's future in doubt as club president Massimo Cellino prepares to return after a ban. Cherry lamented the club's long-standing issues, suggesting it has been in a state of disarray for years.
Green Party leader Natalie Bennett has distanced herself from controversial blog posts made by her boyfriend, Jim Jepps, who ran a site called The Daily Maybe. Jepps has made provocative statements regarding sensitive topics such as rape fantasies and paedophilia, leading the Green Party to clarify that they do not endorse his views. Bennett, who has been dating Jepps for five years, emphasized that he is a private individual not involved in party politics. The couple shares a flat in North London, and while Bennett's political profile has risen, little is known about her personal life compared to other political leaders. The Green Party confirmed that Jepps has not been a member since 2012, the same year Bennett became leader.
Heather Mack, a 19-year-old accused of murdering her mother in Bali, will transfer a significant portion of her $1.3 million trust fund to care for her newborn daughter, Stella. Mack's attorney has filed a petition for approximately $500,000 to cover urgent needs for Stella, who was born in prison. Mack, who is awaiting sentencing alongside her boyfriend, has expressed remorse and is seeking a lighter sentence. The couple is accused of committing the crime in a luxury hotel, and while they initially attempted to flee, they were arrested the next day. Mack has been keeping Stella with her in prison, where she faces challenges related to the baby's care.
North Charleston police are under scrutiny following the shooting of Walter Scott by Officer Michael Slager, particularly regarding the conduct of Slager's colleagues who responded to the scene. A bystander video has raised questions about the officers' accounts, which did not mention that Scott was shot in the back or that they failed to provide proper medical assistance. Scott's father expressed concern that the incident would have been covered up without the video evidence. Slager's initial defense claimed he felt threatened during a struggle for his Taser, but the video contradicts this narrative, showing him shooting Scott in the back. The police department's incident report and the officers' statements have been called into question due to discrepancies with the video evidence. Following the incident, Slager was charged with murder and terminated from the police force, while calls for further accountability and investigation into police conduct continue.
Wayne Rooney has praised Manchester United teammate Marouane Fellaini for his transformation from a scapegoat to a key player, highlighting his recent performances, particularly in the Manchester derby against City. Rooney noted that Fellaini is now being utilized effectively as a second striker, making him a significant threat to opposing defenses. After a challenging first season at United, Fellaini has regained form and confidence, contributing to the team's success with goals and strong performances. United is currently third in the Premier League and is preparing for a match against Chelsea, with Rooney expressing optimism about their progress and training efforts. Manager Louis van Gaal has also acknowledged Fellaini's importance to the team, calling him "almost undroppable."
The FA Cup semi-finals this weekend featured significant television coverage, with both BBC and BT Sport broadcasting from Wembley. Ian Wright expressed discomfort about the semi-finals being held at Wembley, but the venue ultimately provided an exciting atmosphere for the matches. Arsenal defeated Reading, showcasing a thrilling game that engaged viewers, while Reading's goalkeeper Adam Federici experienced a poignant moment of consolation after the loss. The following day, BT Sport focused on Liverpool's Steven Gerrard, who was prominently featured throughout the match against Aston Villa. The coverage included creative segments that highlighted fan involvement, enhancing the overall viewing experience.
Reading's manager, Steve Clarke, has urged his players to treat their upcoming FA Cup semi-final against Arsenal as a regular workday, despite the excitement surrounding the match, which marks the club's first semi-final appearance in 88 years. Clarke emphasized the importance of focusing on the game rather than the occasion, aiming for a win to progress to the final. Reading, who recently defeated Bradford 3-0 to reach this stage, face a challenging task against an in-form Arsenal team. Clarke acknowledged the need for a "perfect game" to overcome the Premier League side, while also noting that Reading has struggled in the Championship this season. The team has no new injury concerns, and Clarke remains hopeful that their successful cup run will continue.
A severe outbreak of HIV infections has emerged in rural Scott and Jackson counties in Indiana, primarily linked to the use of the prescription opioid Opana. The CDC reports that as of Friday, 142 individuals have tested positive for HIV in the area, which has a small population. The outbreak, ongoing since mid-December, has prompted Indiana to declare a public health emergency and implement additional health resources, including a temporary clinic and educational outreach on the dangers of needle sharing. The rise in infections is particularly concerning among younger individuals who are less aware of the risks associated with IV drug use. The state has also initiated a needle exchange program to help reduce new infections. Health officials warn that the situation in Indiana highlights the need for continued vigilance against the spread of HIV and other infectious diseases, especially in areas with high rates of prescription drug abuse.
Jeremy Clarkson will not face prosecution for the incident that led to his dismissal from Top Gear, as the victim, producer Oisin Tymon, chose not to press charges. The North Yorkshire Police concluded their investigation after determining there was no need for further action, following Tymon's request and interviews with witnesses. The altercation occurred when Clarkson became upset over the hotel not serving him a hot meal, resulting in him punching Tymon and verbally abusing him. Despite his sacking, Clarkson is scheduled to participate in rebranded Top Gear Live shows with co-presenters Richard Hammond and James May. The BBC plans to continue the Top Gear franchise, but Hammond and May are not expected to return. Clarkson received public support after the incident, but BBC director-general Tony Hall stated that a line had been crossed, leading to his dismissal. There are speculations about Clarkson's future, including potential moves to other channels and changes within the show's production team.
The U.S. Navy has charged six guards with assaulting detainees at Camp Bucca in Iraq in May, following an investigation by the Army Criminal Investigation Division. The incidents involved two detainees sustaining minor bruises and eight prisoners being confined in a cell treated with a riot control agent. The six guards will face courts-martial, expected to begin within 30 days, while seven other cases were resolved through nonjudicial punishment. The accused guards are part of Navy Provisional Detainee Battalion 4.
In the sentencing phase of Dzhokhar Tsarnaev's trial, jurors heard emotional testimonies from victims and families affected by the Boston Marathon bombings. Tsarnaev, found guilty on all counts, faces the death penalty as the jury considers the impact of his actions. Victims described horrific injuries and the chaos following the blasts, while family members shared their grief over lost loved ones, including Krystle Campbell, Martin Richard, and Lingzi Lu. Prosecutors emphasized the personal stories of the victims to illustrate the profound loss and suffering caused by Tsarnaev's actions, contrasting their lives with Tsarnaev's apparent lack of remorse. The testimonies highlighted the lasting physical and emotional scars left by the attacks, as survivors recounted their traumatic experiences and ongoing struggles.
Jack Wilshere, a talented midfielder who began his career at Luton Town's academy before joining Arsenal, is now mirrored by 11-year-old Charlie Patino, who is also weighing offers from Arsenal, Chelsea, and Tottenham. The Patino family, who are committed to supporting Charlie's football aspirations, are considering these opportunities while ensuring he remains grounded. Charlie, who has shown exceptional skill from a young age, trains extensively at Luton and has been influenced by Spanish football, particularly Barcelona. The family has visited the training facilities of the interested clubs but is taking their time to make a decision, with Luton providing support throughout the process.
A Bangkok Airways plane crashed at Koh Samui airport in Thailand, resulting in the death of the pilot and injuries to 37 others. The ATR-72 turboprop, carrying 68 passengers and four crew members, skidded off the runway after landing. The flight had originated from Krabi, and air traffic control had warned the pilot about unstable winds prior to landing. Seven individuals sustained serious injuries, and emergency responders were attempting to rescue the trapped co-pilot.
Tottenham forward Emmanuel Adebayor has expressed his desire to remain with the club and fight for his position, dismissing transfer rumors. The 31-year-old Togo international took to Twitter to share his appreciation for playing in the Premier League, which he considers the best league in the world. Adebayor, who joined Spurs in 2011, has struggled for form this season, making only 16 appearances and scoring twice, particularly underperforming in a recent League Cup match against Sheffield United. Despite the rise of Harry Kane, which has limited Adebayor's playing time, he remains committed to fulfilling his contract with Tottenham. His last Premier League goal was in October of the previous year.
